A bug report here:
https://developer.mbed.org/questions/7084/PwmOut/#answer7173

Some NXP platforms implement PwmOut HAL using SCT (State Configurable Timer) module and PWM signal doesn't come out when period set more than 16-bit.
This is because SCT operation mode was set in two 16-bit counter mode rather than unified 32-bit counter mode.

``` cpp
#include "mbed.h"

#if defined(TARGET_LPC11U68)
PwmOut pwm(D4);
#else
PwmOut pwm(LED1);
#endif

int main() {

    pwm.write(0.5);
    pwm.period_us(65536); // more than 16-bit : 0x10000

    while (true) {
        wait(1);
    }
}
```

This problem happened in LPC1549, LPC11U68, LPC812 and LPC824.

In
    void USBMSD::disconnect() {
        //De-allocate MSD page size:
        free(page);
        page = NULL;
        USBDevice::disconnect(); 
   }

the isr which also accesses page is deactivated in USBDevice::disconnect();, however page is freed on the heap before that. If the isr interrupts the disconnect right after free(page) it will write to freed memory which could corrupt the heap.

## Problem

When using the PwmOut API the pin is always redirected to pin D13 (aka pwm2/1). All of the following code snippets will output a pwm wave on D13, all these initializations will compile with no error. 

``` c
// doesnt work
PwmOut out(D0); // Doesnt matter what pin you use, All D# and A# will redirect to D13
int main()
{
    out.period(1.0);
    out = 0.5;
    while(1);
}
```

Oddly though the LED's will map correctly. The following snippet does map to LED1

``` c
PwmOut out(LED1);
int main()
{
    out.period(1.0);
    out = 0.5;
    while(1);
}

```
